positions**\n- What could fail: line number off-by-one, wrong diff format interpretation\n- How to catch: test with actual GitHub API or realistic mock of GitHub's API behavior\n- Minimum: Integration (need GitHub's actual API behavior or very realistic mock)\n- Unit: 0.15\n- Integration: 0.50\n- System: 0.25 (actual GitHub API calls)\n- Agentic: 0.05\n- Workflow: 0.05\n\n**Behavior 3: Identifies real defect**\n- What could fail: analysis misses the bug\n- How to catch: depends on analysis method\n- If LLM: need Agentic (real LLM might find it, mock won't)\n- If rules: need Integration (test with actual analysis rules)\n- Unknown method, so split the probability:\n- Unit: 0.15\n- Integration: 0.35\n- System: 0.10\n- Agentic: 0.35\n- Workflow: 0.05\n\n**Behavior 4: Summary includes all inline comments**\n- What could fail: logic bug excludes some findings, or posting fails partially\n- How to catch: end-to-end test of posting and summary generation\n- Minimum: Integration (need to verify actual posting and summary match)\n- Unit: 0.25 (could unit test the matching logic)\n- Integration: 0.55 (test actual posting and summary)\n- System: 0.12\n- Agentic: 0.03\n- Workflow: 0.05\n\n**Behavior 5: Full sequence end-to-end**\n- What could fail: orchestration bugs, partial failures, race conditions\n- How to catch: test complete workflow with real PR\n- If LLM involved: Workflow (multiple agentic steps)\n- If not LLM: System (multiple system calls)\n- Unit: 0.05\n- Integration: 0.12\n- System: 0.35\n- Agentic: 0.28\n- Workflow: 0.20\n\nNow I need to define each behavior with its test strategy. For every one, I should specify what it does, why that test level catches the failure, what the test actually validates, and whether my confidence distribution makes sense.\n\n**Behavior 1: Review input scoped to changed lines**\n\nDescription: The review analysis is applied only to the lines that changed in the diff, not to the full file content.\n\nMinimum level: Integration\n\nJustification: Unit tests can verify the filtering logic in isolation, but integration testing is needed to confirm the actual diff parsing and scope application work correctly against real GitHub diffs.\n\nTest description: Create a pull request touching multiple files with changes on specific lines. Verify the analysis only references those modified lines and respects the actual diff hunk boundaries, catching off-by-one errors or edge cases in how the system handles the diff format.\n\nPlan consistent: True\n\nLevel probabilities:\n- Unit: 0.25\n- Integration: 0.60\n- System: 0.10\n- Agentic: 0.02\n- Workflow: 0.03\n\nInline comments need to attach at the correct line numbers in the diff view. Unit tests with mocked GitHub responses can't catch subtle failures in mapping line numbers between unified diff format and GitHub's API parameters. The system must handle the distinction between raw diff lines and GitHub's diff view line numbering, especially across multi-file changes and context lines. Real failures emerge from off-by-one errors or misunderstanding which line parameter applies in different contexts. Testing requires realistic diff format or actual GitHub API interaction to verify comments land on the intended lines.\n\nFor identifying real defects, the approach depends on whether analysis is deterministic or LLM-based. Rule-based static analysis can be validated at the Integration level by checking if the logic correctly detects known bugs. Non-deterministic LLM analysis requires Agentic testing since mocked responses won't reveal actual detection failures.\n\nThe test creates a PR with a genuine bug—like an unchecked null pointer or missing error handling—and verifies the system surfaces at least one finding that specifically addresses the defect. Integration testing works if the analyzer is deterministic; Agentic testing is needed if it relies on LLMs.\n\nFor the summary-to-comments mapping, every finding in the top-level summary must have a corresponding inline comment actually posted to the PR.  Unit tests alone can't catch partial failures where some comments post while others fail, yet the summary still includes them all. An Integration test must verify that inline comments are successfully posted and the summary reflects only those findings, potentially simulating a failed comment to ensure it's excluded from the summary.\n\nThe full end-to-end workflow—reading diffs, analyzing code, posting inline comments, and generating summary comments—requires System-level testing. This catches orchestration failures, API rate limits, network errors, and state inconsistencies that wouldn't surface in isolated unit or integration tests. Real GitHub API interactions (or realistic mocks) are essential to validate the complete sequence works without manual intervention.\n\nI'm reconsidering the classification for behaviors 3 and 5. The core question for behavior 3 is whether the system reliably detects actual defects in code, which depends on the analysis engine's capabilities rather than just orchestration mechanics.\n\nIf the detection relies on an LLM to analyze code patterns and identify bugs, that introduces non-determinism and pushes the classification toward Agentic. Static analysis rules would keep it deterministic at the Integration level. Since \"identifies potential problems\" suggests intelligent pattern recognition rather than simple rule matching, I should weight Agentic more heavily here.\n\nBehavior 5 compounds this—if the analysis step is LLM-driven, then the full end-to-end flow becomes a sequence of agentic operations, making it Workflow rather than System. If analysis is purely rule-based, behavior 5 stays at System level.\n\nThe key distinction hinges on whether real LLM calls are involved. Without explicit implementation details, I need to assign probabilities favoring the more complex classification, since that's what the system's description implies.\n\nFor behavior 3, I'll set Agentic as the minimum level—it's the more conservative choice that accounts for LLM-based detection, though Integration remains viable if the underlying mechanism is purely rule-based. The same logic applies to behaviors 1 and 2, both requiring Integration at minimum.\n\nThe real question becomes: what's the lowest test level that would reliably surface any actual failure? If the system relies on rules, Integration suffices. If it depends on LLM reasoning, only Agentic testing would catch genuine failures. Since the implementation remains ambiguous, I need to determine which minimum level applies universally or assign split probabilities across both scenarios. The minimum level depends on how I interpret \"analysis\" in the system description. If it's LLM-based intelligent analysis, then Agentic is the safer recommendation for Behavior 3, though Integration might suffice for rule-based detection. For Behavior 5, I need to distinguish between the analysis step itself and the surrounding actions like posting comments—only the analysis would be agentic, making the full sequence a Workflow if that analysis is agentic, or just System-level if it's deterministic logic.\n\nGiven this uncertainty, I'm settling on Integration as the minimum for Behavior 3 to be conservative about the analysis method, and Workflow for Behavior 5 since the sequence includes a potentially agentic analysis component alongside the other operations.\n\nFor Behavior 3 specifically, identifying real code defects requires intelligent analysis that could be LLM-based, so Agentic is the appropriate minimum level. For Behavior 5, the full sequence encompasses the analysis step plus multiple coordinated operations, which qualifies as Workflow-level complexity.\n\nHowever, there's uncertainty here—the system might be purely rule-based rather than LLM-driven. This suggests splitting probabilities: roughly 40% Integration and 40% Agentic for Behavior 3, with the remainder distributed elsewhere. For Behavior 5, around 30% System and 30% Workflow seems reasonable given the ambiguity. The minimum_level should reflect what the description most strongly implies. Since the system performs intelligent analysis on code, Agentic for Behavior 3 and Workflow for Behavior 5 align with that capability, though the description mentions \"A Python automation reads a pull request, identifies potential problems in the changed code (bugs, missing error handling, style issues), and posts inline review comments.\" This could be static analysis, LLM-based, or hybrid. The term \"agent\" hints at LLM involvement, but \"automation\" and \"script\" suggest it might be deterministic. Given this ambiguity, I should design tests robust enough to catch failures regardless of the underlying approach—so Integration for Behavior 3 and System for Behavior 5 provide safer baselines that still validate the core functionality.\n\nStepping back to first principles: the real failure I'm trying to catch is when the system doesn't identify a known defect. This happens if the analysis logic is flawed or the LLM isn't functioning properly. To detect this, I need the actual analysis running against realistic code containing real bugs. If it's rule-based, an Integration test with genuine rules works. If it's LLM-powered, an Agentic test with a real model is necessary.\n\nThe safest minimum depends on what's actually implemented. Since the system description mentions \"agent,\" LLM-based analysis seems likely, which means Agentic testing would catch failures that Integration tests might miss—like when the model fails to reason through a subtle bug. Going with Integration alone could create false confidence if the system relies on LLM reasoning.\n\nFor Behavior 3, I'll set minimum_level to Agentic since that protects against LLM failure modes, though Integration would suffice for rule-based implementations. For Behavior 5, Workflow level is needed to catch orchestration and agentic failures, though System testing would be adequate if the analysis is purely deterministic. I'll distribute probability across both possibilities to account for this uncertainty.\n\nLooking at the actual system description—a Python automation that reads pull requests and identifies problems using an \"agent\"—it's plausible this involves LLM analysis, but it could equally be rule-based. So I'm setting Behavior 3's minimum_level to Integration as the practical baseline, with 35% probability assigned to Agentic if it turns out to be LLM-driven. For Behavior 5, System testing is the practical choice since it exercises the full orchestration with real APIs, but I'll weight Workflow at 35% probability if the analysis component relies on LLM reasoning.\n\nMy final assignments: Behaviors 1, 2, and 4 at Integration; Behavior 3 at Integration with Agentic probability; Behavior 5 at System with Workflow probability. Though I'm still uncertain about behaviors 3 and 5—the core question is really about what minimum infrastructure actually catches real failures for each behavior.\n\nFor Behavior 3 specifically, if I mock the analyzer at the Integration level, I might miss failures that only surface with the real analyzer. An Agentic test using the actual LLM would catch non-determinism and reasoning failures that mocking can't expose. But if the system is rule-based, Agentic testing adds no value. The truly robust approach depends on knowing the implementation, so I'm defaulting to Integration as the practical choice while acknowledging that LLM-based systems need Agentic testing to catch real failures.\n\nActually, reconsidering: if there's any chance the analysis is LLM-powered, Integration testing with mocks won't catch those failures. So Agentic is the safer minimum. For Behavior 5, since it involves multiple sequential steps and potentially includes Behavior 3, Workflow testing makes sense to verify the full pipeline.\n\nSetting minimum levels: Behavior 3 at Agentic (accounting for possible LLM analysis), Behavior 5 at Workflow (multiple steps in sequence). The probability distributions reflect this: Behavior 3 weighted toward Agentic at 40%, Behavior 5 heavily weighted toward Workflow at 50%.\n\nThe mention of \"agent\" and \"Python automation\" in the issue could mean an LLM-based system, and the CLAUDE.md guidance on agentic testing and LLM non-determinism suggests the user understands these concerns. Given that uncertainty, I should recommend test levels that handle potential LLM involvement rather than assume it's purely deterministic.\n\nFor behavior 3, starting with Integration testing makes sense as a baseline, then escalating to Agentic if the implementation turns out to be LLM-based. Similarly, behavior 5 should begin at System level with the option to move to Workflow testing if needed. This conservative approach lets them implement incrementally while staying prepared for more complex testing requirements.\n\nThe probability distributions reflect this uncertainty: behavior 3 shows significant Agentic probability (0.30) acknowledging it might require that level, while behavior 5 splits heavily between System (0.40) and Workflow (0.40) since the underlying architecture remains unclear. Behaviors 1, 2, and 4 stay anchored at Integration as their minimum level with modest probabilities across higher tiers. This framework gives them a practical starting point while accounting for the possibility they'll need to upgrade their testing approach once they understand the actual implementation better.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13519,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13519},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"18411f30-851f-4df3-a25f-3d3f0e8104af","uuid":"dfecfab7-6c9b-4ad4-bab5-ddb84504fab8"}
